<p><b>Power-to-weight ratio</b> (<b>PWR</b>, also called <b>specific power<=
/b>, or <b>power-to-mass ratio</b>) is a calculation commonly applied to <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engine" title=3D"Engine">engines</a>=
 and mobile power sources to enable the comparison of one unit or design to=
 another. Power-to-weight ratio is a measurement of actual performance of a=
ny engine or power source. It is also used as a measurement of performance =
of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vehicle" title=3D"Vehicle">ve=
hicle</a> as a whole, with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eng=
ine_power" title=3D"Engine power">engine's power output</a> being divided b=
y the weight (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=3D"Ma=
ss">mass</a>) of the vehicle, to give a metric that is independent of the v=
ehicle's size. Power-to-weight is often quoted by manufacturers at the peak=
 value, but the actual value may vary in use and variations will affect per=
formance.
</p><p>The inverse of power-to-weight, <b>weight-to-power ratio</b> (power =
loading) is a calculation commonly applied to aircraft, cars, and vehicles =
in general, to enable the comparison of one vehicle's performance to anothe=
r. Power-to-weight ratio is equal to thrust per unit mass multiplied by the=
 velocity of any vehicle.
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Power-to-weight_(specific_p=
ower)"><span id=3D"Power-to-weight_.28specific_power.29"></span>Power-to-we=
ight (specific power)</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPower-to-weight_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D=
"Edit section: Power-to-weight (specific power)"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The power-to-weight ratio (specific power) is defined as the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(physics)" title=3D"Power (physics)">po=
wer</a> generated by the engine(s) divided by the mass. In this context, th=
e term "weight" can be considered a misnomer, as it colloquially refers to =
mass. In a zero-gravity (weightless) environment, the power-to-weight ratio=
 would not be considered infinite.
</p><p>A typical turbocharged V8 diesel engine might have an engine power o=
f 250&nbsp;kW (340&nbsp;hp) and a mass of 380&nbsp;kg (840&nbsp;lb),<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-gmduramax_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Power-to-weight_ratio#cite_note-gmduramax-1"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> givin=
g it a power-to-weight ratio of 0.65&nbsp;kW/kg&nbsp;(0.40&nbsp;hp/lb).
</p><p>Examples of high power-to-weight ratios can often be found in turbin=
es. This is because of their ability to operate at very high speeds. For ex=
ample, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_Shuttle" title=3D=
"Space Shuttle">Space Shuttle</a>'s main engines used <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbopump" title=3D"Turbopump">turbopumps</a> (machines=
 consisting of a pump driven by a turbine engine) to feed the propellants (=
liquid oxygen and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liquid_hydrogen"=
 title=3D"Liquid hydrogen">liquid hydrogen</a>) into the engine's combustio=
n chamber. The original liquid hydrogen turbopump is similar in size to an =
automobile engine (weighing approximately 352 kilograms (775&nbsp;lb)) and =
produces 72,000&nbsp;hp (54&nbsp;MW)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ssmetpb1_2-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power-to-weight_rat=
io#cite_note-ssmetpb1-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for a power-to-weight ratio of 153&nbs=
p;kW/kg&nbsp;(93&nbsp;hp/lb).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Physical_interpretation">Ph=
ysical interpretation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPower-to-weight_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D=
"Edit section: Physical interpretation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_mechanics" title=
=3D"Classical mechanics">classical mechanics</a>, instantaneous <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(physics)" title=3D"Power (physics)">po=
wer</a> is the limiting value of the average work done per unit time as the=
 time interval =CE=94<i>t</i> approaches zero (i.e. the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">derivative</a> with =
respect to time of the work done).
</p>
