<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Heat_engines_and_heat_pumps=
">Heat engines and heat pumps</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DPower-to-weight_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" =
title=3D"Edit section: Heat engines and heat pumps"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Thermal energy is made up from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sensible_heat" title=3D"Sensible heat">molecular</a> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinetic_energy" title=3D"Kinetic energy">kinetic energy<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_heat" title=3D"Late=
nt heat">latent</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_(matter)=
" title=3D"Phase (matter)">phase</a> energy. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Heat_engine" title=3D"Heat engine">Heat engines</a> are able to =
convert thermal energy in the form of a temperature gradient between a hot =
source and a cold sink into other desirable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Work_(physics)" title=3D"Work (physics)">mechanical work</a>. <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_pump" title=3D"Heat pump">Heat p=
umps</a> take <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Work_(physics)" titl=
e=3D"Work (physics)">mechanical work</a> to regenerate thermal energy in a =
temperature gradient. Standard definitions should be used when interpreting=
 how the propulsive power of a jet or rocket engine is transferred to its v=
ehicle.
</p>
