d electromotive generators"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_motor" title=3D"Ele=
ctric motor">electric motor</a> uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Electrical_energy" title=3D"Electrical energy">electrical energy</a> to =
provide <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Work_(physics)" title=3D"W=
ork (physics)">mechanical work</a>, usually through the interaction of a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fields" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Magnetic fields">magnetic field</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_conductor" title=3D"Electrical conductor">curr=
ent-carrying conductors</a>. By the interaction of mechanical work on an el=
ectrical conductor in a magnetic field, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Electrical_energy" title=3D"Electrical energy">electrical energy</a> =
can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_generator" title=
=3D"Electric generator">generated</a>.
</p>
