<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Thermoelectric_generators_a=
nd_electrothermal_actuators">Thermoelectric generators and electrothermal a=
ctuators</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPow=
er-to-weight_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Thermoelectric generators and electrothermal actuators"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A variety of effects can be harnessed to produce <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Thermoelectricity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Thermoe=
lectricity">thermoelectricity</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Thermionic_emission" title=3D"Thermionic emission">thermionic emission</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyroelectricity" title=3D"Pyroel=
ectricity">pyroelectricity</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Piezoelectricity" title=3D"Piezoelectricity">piezoelectricity</a>. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_resistance" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Electrical resistance">Electrical resistance</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferromagnetism" title=3D"Ferromagnetism">=
ferromagnetism</a> of materials can be harnessed to generate thermoacoustic=
 energy from an electric current.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Electrochemical_(galvanic)_=
and_electrostatic_cell_systems"><span id=3D"Electrochemical_.28galvanic.29_=
and_electrostatic_cell_systems"></span>Electrochemical (galvanic) and elect=
rostatic cell systems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPower-to-weight_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Edit section: Electrochemical (galvanic) and electrostatic cell systems=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"(Closed_cell)_batteries"><s=
pan id=3D".28Closed_cell.29_batteries"></span>(Closed cell) batteries</h4><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</spa=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower-to-weight_r=
atio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: (Closed cel=
l) batteries"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>All electrochemical cell batteries deliver a changing voltage as their c=
hemistry changes from "charged" to "discharged". A nominal output voltage a=
nd a cutoff voltage are typically specified for a battery by its manufactur=
er. The output voltage falls to the cutoff voltage when the battery becomes=
 "discharged". The nominal output voltage is always less than the open-circ=
uit voltage produced when the battery is "charged". The temperature of a ba=
ttery can affect the power it can deliver, where lower temperatures reduce =
power. Total energy delivered from a single charge cycle is affected by bot=
h the battery temperature and the power it delivers. If the temperature low=
ers or the power demand increases, the total energy delivered at the point =
of "discharge" is also reduced.
</p><p>Battery discharge profiles are often described in terms of a factor =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battery_(electricity)#Capacity_=
and_discharging" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Battery (electricity)">batt=
ery capacity</a>. For example, a battery with a nominal capacity quoted in =
ampere-hours (Ah) at a C/10 rated discharge current (derived in amperes) ma=
y safely provide a higher discharge current&nbsp;=E2=80=93 and therefore hi=
gher power-to-weight ratio&nbsp;=E2=80=93 but only with a lower energy capa=
city. Power-to-weight ratio for batteries is therefore less meaningful with=
out reference to corresponding energy-to-weight ratio and cell temperature.=
 This relationship is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peu=
kert%27s_law" title=3D"Peukert's law">Peukert's law</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power-to-=
weight_ratio#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
