<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Electrostatic,_electrolytic=
_and_electrochemical_capacitors"><span id=3D"Electrostatic.2C_electrolytic_=
and_electrochemical_capacitors"></span>Electrostatic, electrolytic and elec=
trochemical capacitors</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.p=
hp?title=3DPower-to-weight_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=
=3D"Edit section: Electrostatic, electrolytic and electrochemical capacitor=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capacitor" title=3D"Capacitor">=
Capacitors</a> store electric charge onto two electrodes separated by an el=
ectric field semi-insulating (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diel=
ectric" title=3D"Dielectric">dielectric</a>) medium. Electrostatic capacito=
rs feature planar electrodes onto which electric charge accumulates. <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrolytic_capacitor" title=3D"Electro=
lytic capacitor">Electrolytic capacitors</a> use a liquid electrolyte as on=
e of the electrodes and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double=
_layer_(interfacial)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Double layer (interfac=
ial)">electric double layer effect</a> upon the surface of the dielectric-e=
lectrolyte boundary to increase the amount of charge stored per unit volume=
. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_double-layer_capacitor"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electric double-layer capacitor">Electric d=
ouble-layer capacitors</a> extend both electrodes with a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanopore" title=3D"Nanopore">nanoporous</a> material=
 such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activated_carbon" title=
=3D"Activated carbon">activated carbon</a> to significantly increase the su=
rface area upon which electric charge can accumulate, reducing the dielectr=
ic medium to nanopores and a very thin high <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Permittivity" title=3D"Permittivity">permittivity</a> separator.
</p><p>While capacitors tend not to be as temperature sensitive as batterie=
s, they are significantly capacity constrained and without the strength of =
chemical bonds suffer from self-discharge. Power-to-weight ratio of capacit=
ors is usually higher than batteries because charge transport units within =
the cell are smaller (electrons rather than ions), however energy-to-weight=
 ratio is conversely usually lower.
</p>
