<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Vehicles">Vehicles</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower-to-weight_rati=
o&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Vehicles"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>Power-to-weight ratios for vehicles are usually calculated using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curb_weight" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Curb weight">curb weight</a> (for cars) or wet weight (for motorcycles)=
, that is, excluding weight of the driver and any cargo. This could be slig=
htly misleading, especially with regard to motorcycles, where the driver mi=
ght weigh 1/3 to 1/2 as much as the vehicle itself. In the sport of competi=
tive cycling athlete's performance is increasingly being expressed in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VAM_(bicycling)" title=3D"VAM (bicyclin=
g)">VAMs</a> and thus as a power-to-weight ratio in W/kg. This can be measu=
red through the use of a bicycle powermeter or calculated from measuring in=
cline of a road climb and the rider's time to ascend it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-vam_104-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
wer-to-weight_ratio#cite_note-vam-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Locomotives">Locomotives</h=
4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower-to-weigh=
t_ratio&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Locomoti=
ves"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locomotive" title=3D"Locomoti=
ve">locomotive</a> generally must be heavy in order to develop enough <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adhesion_railway" title=3D"Adhesion rai=
lway">adhesion on the rails</a> to start a train. As the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient_of_friction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Coefficient of friction">coefficient of friction</a> between steel whee=
ls and rails seldom exceeds 0.25 in most cases, improving a locomotive's po=
wer-to-weight ratio is often counterproductive. However, the choice of powe=
r transmission system, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Var=
iable-frequency_drive" title=3D"Variable-frequency drive">variable-frequenc=
y drive</a> versus <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DC_motor" title=
=3D"DC motor">direct-current drive</a>, may support a higher power-to-weigh=
t ratio by better managing propulsion power.
</p>
