<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Human">Human</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower-to-weight_ratio&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Human"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Power-to-weight ratio is important in cycling, since it determines accel=
eration and the speed during <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hillc=
limbing_(cycling)" title=3D"Hillclimbing (cycling)">hill climbs</a>. Since =
a cyclist's power-to-weight output decreases with fatigue, it is normally d=
iscussed with relation to the length of time that he or she maintains that =
power. A professional cyclist can produce over 20&nbsp;W/kg (0.012&nbsp;hp/=
lb) as a five-second maximum.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-648" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power-to-weight_ratio#cite_note-648=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>648<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
